xcsBWXJm_aY.title: GRILLED EEL IN JAPAN ♦ Trying Unagi in Narita!
xcsBWXJm_aY.description:
Today we're trying Grilled Eel in Narita! Called "unagi" in Japanese, there are many restaurants selling this dish on Nakamachi Street. Which does one choose? Most shops had employees standing at the storefront, warmly inviting passersby inside. Mommy Oh and I were instantly drawn into the shop displaying their food preparation. In the public eye, men were skewering eel and sharpening their knife. We order three items: eel over rice, miso soup with carp, and assorted pickled vegetables. We also explore the Naritasan Park and temple. Watch the video to see the food adventure unfold :)

▼▼▼▼▼

2xknxMCktM4.title: HALAL AIRPLANE FOOD on Singapore Airlines ► SFO to SIN
2xknxMCktM4.description:
Today we're flying 17 hours to Singapore from San Francisco! All our meals during this flight will be Muslim, which means "no alcohol, pork, pig py-products, ham, or bacon is used in the preparation of the meal" (according to Singapore Airlines). For special meals based on dietary preferences and religious purposes, be sure to request on the airline website before your departure. No, I am not religious, but I like to try various cuisine on my flights :) 

We were served two meals during the flight. If you get hungry in between, snacks are available. Watch the video for more details!

IFnq7hwBb_w.title: $300 A Night Japanese Hotel ♦ Ryokan & Kaiseki Dining
IFnq7hwBb_w.description:
What's it like staying at a $300+ a night hotel in Tokyo, Japan? Today I give you a tour of the Ryokan and Western style rooms at Gajoen. For brunch and dinner, we check out restaurants on the ground level. We try Kaiseki (traditional Japanese multi-course meal) at Tofutei and Tokyo-style Chinese dishes at Shunyuki. On our first night, we stay in a spacious modern room. For the second night, we are transferred to a traditional Japanese style room, but end up moving to another modern room. Why? Watch the video to find out! And also get delicious close-ups of artfully prepared kaiseki dishes :)

Thanks so much to Fei for kindly booking this baller hotel for my 30th birthday! You think you can get away with spoiling me?! I'm coming after you Fei! Throwing feasts your way and more! :D

G6ow0HjRuiE.description:

Today I give you a tour of a Five Star Hotel we stayed in Las Vegas! The building was so big that we got lost multiple times. Can you believe it's home to more than 15 restaurants? All under one roof, including a casino, spa, nightclub, fitness center, swimming pool, and more. We stayed for five days and four nights, which was not enough time to try everything inside. SO MUCH FOOD AND ENTERTAINMENT. After all, we're in the city of excess. Watch the video for the peek inside! (Note: This video was filmed during CES 2018. fH26mMZmnXs.title: VR Horror Hospital Freakout - CES 2018

P9VWR5ZTfoI.title: ALL YOU CAN EAT BUFFET in Las Vegas
P9VWR5ZTfoI.description:
Today we're eating at an all-you-can-eat buffet! Said to be one of the best places for AYCE dining in Las Vegas, we head to Wynn Hotel's The Buffet. Bring an extra stomach because the options are endless! From Mexican to Japanese to Chinese to Vegan cuisine, there's something for everyone. Having just one bite of every dish will leave you feeling full. 

After filming this video, I have concluded: get one plate of fresh food at a time instead of what I did. This will allow you to enjoy juicier meat and steamier bites :) Stay tuned for more Las Vegas & CES videos to come! 

The Buffet at Wynn
Address: 3131 S Las Vegas Blvd, Las Vegas, NV 89109
Prices vary for breakfast, lunch and dinner. The following info is based on January 2018:
+ Breakfast (Monday-Friday, 7:30-11am) = $24.99
+ Lunch (Monday-Friday, 11am-3:30pm) = $28.99
+ Dinner (Sunday-Thursday, 3:30pm-9:30pm) = $42.99
+ Gourmet Brunch (Saturday-Sunday, 7:30-3:30pm) = $35:99
+ Gourmet Dinner (Friday-Saturday, 3:30pm-9:30pm) = $49.99

_H_ITYhNMYU.title: Japanese PRISON THEMED Restaurant in Tokyo
_H_ITYhNMYU.description:
😘 Subscribe for more munchies: http://bit.ly/MissMinaYT
👕 Get my shirt: http://bit.ly/MissMinaMerch
🎥 MY CAMERA & VLOGGING GEAR: https://www.missmina.co/blog/my-2020-vlogging-gear

Ready or not, we're eating inside a prison cell tonight! Specifically a medical prison. Japan is famous for its themed restaurants and we couldn't leave without trying one. We head to Dogenzaka in Tokyo and get spooked. Little did we know it'd feel like Halloween all over again. 

From livers to brains, we order it all. Note: The liver is actually a red omelette and the brain is beef stuffed with a salad. And wait... is that strawberry jelly on a REAL pad?! Watch the video to get freaked out with us!

Be sure to check out my friend's channel!

8ZJFbhwuK78.title: HALAL FOOD IN SINGAPORE
8ZJFbhwuK78.description:
Today we're trying Halal cuisine at Singapore's Botanic Garden! We dig into Chili Crab with a twist. We also try 48-Hour Sous Vide Spare Ribs (Blackmore Wagyu) and Lemongrass & Ginger Prawn Salad. To cool off from the humidity, we drink Grapefruit Juice with House-Made Tarragon Infusion and Lychee Juice with Thyme Infusion. 

That's not all! For dessert we try Ginger & Almond Nougatine Parfait with coconut mousse, compressed pineapple, and dehydrated coconut flesh. 5Q46FhpeE2w.title: South Indian Food in Singapore ♦ MY LAST MUKBANG
5Q46FhpeE2w.description:
Today we're in Little India of Singapore! There's a restaurant nearby known for South Indian food and its idlis, which means... we are digging in! I take you on a tour of the neighborhood and pick up various dishes including (the following Romanizations were taken from the menu): 

+ Pongal
+ Sweet Pongal
+ Sambarvadai (aka: Sambar Vada)
+ Masalvadai (aka: Masala Vadai)
+ Meduvadai (aka: Medu Vada)
+ Uttappam 
+ Butter Uttappam
+ Masala Dosai (aka: dosa)
+ Idli
+ Ghee Podi Idli
+ Jigarthanda

In the previous video, I revealed why I stopped making mukbang videos. Overeating on a weekly basis had negative health effects, so this will be my last mukbang. I'll still make videos on this channel though! Stay tuned for food and travel vlogs... without the overeating :)

2_V3mkSbqbg.description:

em0Qn6fLtwU.title: Meal Prepping ♦ What I Eat Everyday for Breakfast
em0Qn6fLtwU.description:
Many of our fellow viewers have been asking me: How do you stay slim after eating so much? Today I'm showing you what I eat on a daily basis (particularly for breakfast)! On-camera, I eat everything from street food to raw meat to bugs. Off-camera, I balance it all out with a more calm diet, one that consists largely of vegetables. Of course, I'd love to eat flavorful food every single meal! But in terms of health, one must practice a little discipline :) 

In every meal-prepping session, I cook about seven containers of veggies and eat a serving for breakfast everyday with a handful of nuts or sun-dried tomatoes. I might have a second container for lunch or dinner, usually paired with salmon. 

This is the sort of meal-prepping while traveling (when I have access to a kitchen, which is why I prefer staying at Airbnbs instead of hotels). Hope you guys found this helpful!

pnK6XWBhuuk.title: Roasted Suckling Pig in Bali (TRAVEL VLOG)
pnK6XWBhuuk.description:
Today we try Babi Guling (Roasted Suckling Pig), an in-your-face dish that reminds you what you are about to eat was once alive. Its presentation may be tragic, but also honest. As opposed to the abstracted meat we are typically served in other restaurants, such as hamburgers, steak, so forth. 

In this travel vlog, we also check out a hidden bridge that not even many locals know about (or so a local tells me). We watch a live performance called the Barong Dance, a play representing the battle between good and evil. 

My host father Jiwa, whom I hired to drive us for the day,  takes us to Keramas Beach (black sand beach) and his buddy's cafe. During the garden tour, we smell fresh leaves of citronella, lemongrass and cinnamon. We even chew on some betel leaf, which has a surprisingly broad taste range! From salty to sweet to spicy, it's got it all. Watch the video to see the adventure unfold :)

My host father Jiwa, whom I hired to drive us for the day,  takes us to Keramas Beach (black sand beach) and his buddy's cafe. During the garden tour, we smell fresh leaves of citronella, lemongrass and cinnamon. We even chew on some betel leaf, which has a surprisingly broad taste range! From salty to sweet to spicy, it's got it all. Watch the video to see the adventure unfold :)

N6k-xvVhXoo.title: Chinese Airplane Food ► Dim Sum & Braised Beef on Singapore Airlines from Hong Kong to San Francisco
N6k-xvVhXoo.description:
❤️ instagram: @missminaoh
😘 subscribe for more munchies: http://bit.ly/MissMinaYT
💙 my shop: http://bit.ly/MissMinaMerch

Today we're flying from Hong Kong to San Francisco via Singapore Airlines! It's a 12-hour flight in Economy Class and we are served two meals: dinner and breakfast. Both of which are Teochew, referring to an area in eastern Guangdong, China. An Indian selection is available as well. For particular diets, you can request online in advance. 

For supper, we have the choice of Sauteed Egg, Shimp, and Spring Onion with Steamed Rice or Braised Beef with Roasted Garlic Thyme Sauce (served with a vegetable medley and mashed potatoes). I order the latter. 

For breakfast, we have three options: Parsley Omelette, Dim Sum, or Steamed Rice Cake (Idli, Kesar Upma, Sambar). I chose DIM SUM!!! Excuse me, can't help but go a bit crazy around them :) The specific types of dim sum served: Yam Cake, Turnip Cake, and Pork Siew Mai. 

How does the food taste? What about the in-flight experience? Watch the video to find out the details!

QiBOob5OL38.title: BALI TRAVEL VLOG ♦ Off The Beaten Path
QiBOob5OL38.description:
Ready or not, we’re going on a full-day Bali adventure! From street food to experiencing the local life to crashing a wedding (kinda), it’s all in this travel vlog. We start off the day with a Balinese breakfast prepared by my host mother. Then my host father Jiwa, whom I hired to drive me around for the day, takes us off the beaten path. We get a peep into gamelan (traditional ensemble music) and condong (Balinese dance) practices. 

On the way to eat Santan Kemangi (fried gurame fish with coconut milk and basil), we stop by the Puppet Shop where a craftman creates headdresses, costumes and more. At the water temple Tirta Empul, we get spiritual cleansing. Then soak in the view of rice terraces. Watch the video to see the eventful day unfold! 

FEATURED PLACES (in order of appearance): 
+ SMKN 3 Sukawati (in Batubulan) 
+ Stone carving shop (8°36'24.2"S 115°15'09.5"E)
+ Prapen Jewelry & Artifacts
+ Puppet Shop (8°35’31.1”S, 115°16’34.7”E)
+ Warung Mina (8°36'39.0"S 115°13'14.9”E) 
+ Bakso Stall (sorry guys, exact location unknown) 
+ Gunung Kawi
+ Pura Tirta Empul
+ Tegallalang Rice Terrace
+ Village of White Herons 

Note: This video was filmed in October 2016. It is not sponsored.

l4HMtrf9-7A.title: Roasted Goose Noodles in Hong Kong
l4HMtrf9-7A.description:
We begin the day with Roast Goose over Noodles. You can choose to eat it with rice instead. I personally like to have the goose with the soup as it hydrates the meat. Slippery, soft, slightly tough... This bowl has a variety of textures!

Afterwards we walk over to a hidden bookshop (Flow Books) where we meet bookkeeper Surdham. He shows us vintage books, each containing pages of unique history. 

Upon taking the metro to Mong Kok, we try vegetarian food near Sneaker Street and Ladies Market. We indulge in the street food scene and head back to Discovery Bay for dinner. Ready or not, watch the video to see the day unfold!

Featured places (in order of appearance):
+ Yat Lok (34-38 Stanley St, Central)
+ Flow Books: https://www.flowbooks.net/
+ Veggie Family (145 Sai Yee St, Mong Kok)
+ Ladies Market (39 Tung Choi Street, Mong Kok)

HYHgSgmf1tk.title: Mexican Street Food in LA ► Guatemalan Night Market
HYHgSgmf1tk.description:
What's street food in Southern California like? We check out the Guatemalan Night Market in LA on a Friday night and try Tacos Chapines, Garnachas (small corn tortillas fried with meat), Chicken Tamales (masa steamed in corn husk), Carne Asada Tacos (marinated/grilled beef in a fried tortilla), Mexican-style Flan, and Cheesy Blue Corn Quesadilla with Steak and Mushroom. Other dishes you can eat include Tostadas (deep-fried tortilla topped with meat, vegetables and beans), Fried Chicken, Burritos and more! Watch to see the food adventure unfold :)

Address: The night market is located in Little Central America at the intersection of Bonnie Brae and 6th Street (in Los Angeles).

849jKdXD138.title: INDONESIAN FOOD in Borneo (ft. Nadia Vega)
849jKdXD138.description:
Today we eat Indonesian food on our drive from Balikpapan to Samarinda! Dishes we try include Tahu Sumedang (deep-fried tofu from Sumedang), various Gorengan (fritters) containing banana, chocolate and tofu, Cireng (deep-fried fritter made tapioca flour), Young Coconut sweetened by brown sugar, Kampung Nasi Goreng (Village Fried Rice), Karedok (raw veggie salad with peanut sauce dressing), and Nasi Bakar (steamed rice in banana leaf). 

Joining us is Nadia Vega, Indonesian actress and singer. Her friend Bruno kindly names what all the dishes are. He also treats me to Durian Ice Cream. Upon the Indo lunch, we prepare for the Nadia's performance. Watch the video to see the action unfold!

56cB91lRwDk.title: Mie Goreng ► Indonesian Fried Noodles in Bali
56cB91lRwDk.description:
Today we're trying Mie Goreng (Indonesian Fried Noodles) in Ubud at a restaurant called Warung Komang. We pair our meal with Palm Wine, which makes the weather feels even warmer! For dessert we cross the street to Earth Cafe & Market. A must-visit for especially vegans and those searching for healthy yet yummy sweets. We enjoy Chocolate Mud Cake with Coconut Gelato. The dark of the night sets in and we head to Blanco Museum for the closing ceremony of the Ubud Writers & Readers Festival. Watch to see the day unfold!

Yeh_GgdOUyM.title: What I Packed for 6 Months in Asia
Yeh_GgdOUyM.description:
What's in my bag? Many of our fellow viewers asked me, "What did you bring when traveling for six months?" Every country I visited, I brought my backpack that contained my tech, my main bag that held my clothes and toiletry, and my mini messenger bag which I carried with me on daily outings. Watch the video for the details! 

READ THE BLOG POST FOR MORE TIPS: https://www.missmina.co/blog/2017/9/27/what-i-packed-for-six-months-abroad-as-a-solo-female-traveler

The camera I filmed this video with: http://amzn.to/2isP1PK
The newer model of my camera: http://amzn.to/2j7X5ES

***************
LIST OF ITEMS I BROUGHT:
+ my main bag: http://amzn.to/2xl3d5e
+ my backpack 
+ my mini messenger bag (bought in Singapore from prior trip)

TOILETRY BAG: http://amzn.to/2fhMQQA
+ second pair of glasses
+ tweezers for eyebrow and armpit
+ electronic toothbrush
+ tongue scraper
+ floss
+ nail cutter
+ earplugs 
+ hair ties
+ headband
+ hairbrush
+ feminine products (ie: pads, tampons, pantyliners) 
+ Q-tips (from hotel)
+ extra floss sticks for day bag (bought in Korea)
+ razor with soap (bought in Thailand) 
+ nail polish (bought in Korea) 
+ facial masks (bought in Korea) 
+ acne patch (bought in Korea) 
+ bandages (bought in Bali) 
+ two small bars of soap (from previous hotels) 
+ one-time use shampoo/conditioner (some Airbnbs I stayed at did not provided essentials) 

MAKEUP: 
+ bareMinerals matte foundation: http://amzn.to/2yoeSys
+ bareMinerals warmth: http://amzn.to/2hhvqk3
+ foundation brush
+ blush brush
+ eyebrow pencil (bought in Korea)
+ liquid eyeliner (bought in Korea)

CARRY-ON LIQUIDS BAG: http://amzn.to/2wvrln0
+ primer
+ BB cream 
+ Stila concealer: http://amzn.to/2xPyxul
+ toothpaste
+ mini toothpaste for day bag
+ makeup remover by Face Shop
+ insect repellent: http://amzn.to/2ypLGHI
+ sunscreen (bought in Korea)
+ toner (bought in Korea)
+ lotion (bought in Korea)
+ clay mask (bought in Korea and Bali) 

CLOTHES: 
+ three jeans
+ four casual button-down shirts
+ two bras
+ two pajama shorts
+ one pajama shirt
+ eight undies
+ Uniqlo ultra light down jacket
+ six tanks (my white tanks got destroyed from stains, so replaced them with colorful ones) 
+ one loose Aladdin pants (bought in Bali)
+ one slightly fancy shorts (bought in Chiang Mai)
+ one skirt for special occasions (bought in Korea)
+ one blouse for special occasions (bought in Korea)

ACCESSORIES: 
+ one pair of flip flops
+ one pair of sneakers
+ short-term use indoor slippers (from hotel in Indonesia)
+ nine pairs of socks (bought some from Korea and Vietnam)
+ one thin scarf (bought in Vietnam)
+ one pashmina scarf (bought in Thailand) 
+ one pair of earrings (from friend in Bali)
+ one pair of high heels (from Bali)
+ two foldable bags (from Bali and Thailand) 

TECH (since I’m a vlogger): 
+ laptop
+ laptop charger
+ vlogging camera: http://amzn.to/2fj06o6
+ vlog camera charger
+ extra camera battery
+ extra memory card for camera: http://amzn.to/2xleoLd
+ earphones
+ selfie stick: http://amzn.to/2xgajq0 
+ convertor 
+ USB cords & charger
+ two external hard-drives (I brought a third one, but mailed it home to secure a portion of my footage)
+ anti-static bags (bought in Korea and used to securely send my third external hard-drive by mail) 
+ mouse (my first one broke, so I bought a replacement in Thailand) 

OTHER: 
+ copy of passport in each bag
+ copy of traveler’s insurance
+ microfiber towel
+ anti-diarrheal pills
+ Pepto-Bismol
+ Motrin
+ measuring tape
+ my vision board
+ book
+ flask (gift from my gift in Indonesia) 
+ postcards & postcard envelope (bought from various countries) 

Last but most definitely not least: REMEMBER TO PACK YOUR PASSPORT!

jQLzRP8UNUE.title: Hong Kong Breakfast ► Perfect Scrambled Eggs & Buttery French Toast
jQLzRP8UNUE.description:
Today we try juicy scrambled eggs and more at the infamous Australia Dairy Company! We join forces with my college friend Kashing and his wife to eat breakfast for dinner. Three combos are presented to us: Fast Combo, Breakfast Combo, and Standard Combo. We choose the latter. Our Standard Combo included Hong Kong Style Milk Tea, Buttery French Toast, Spaghetti in Chicken Soup, Plain O’ Bread with Butter and a side of Ham, and of course, the yummy Scrambled Eggs. 

We also visit MBA Art Workshop to get in touch with our inner artist. Thanks so much to Jessie for the meditative painting session :)

KhFDAe5LXh8.description:
Today we're trying Egg Tarts all around Hong Kong! We begin at the famous Tai Cheong Bakery to find out for ourselves: is it worth the hype? For round two, we check out Macau Restaurant where they serve Portuguese Egg Tarts and other goodies. And that's not all! We head north for Kam Wah Cafe & Bakery in Mong Kok for our final egg-licious munchies. Which tastes the yummiest? Watch to find out the details! :)

2Sz_Phzqr4M.title: Taiwanese Street Food at Jiufen ft. Ice Cream Burritos
2Sz_Phzqr4M.description:
Today we're heading all the way to Jiufen, the mountain town of Taiwan that inspired Miyazaki's "Spirited Away." We try various food offered by the street vendors, including Ice Cream Burritos (peanut cilantro ice cream wraps), Grilled Mochi with Tapioca Balls, Lu Rou Fan (Braised Pork Rice Bowl) and more. 

Joining us is my Airbnb housemate Steve! You've seen him before in my Shilin Night Market video. Afterwards we check out the Gold Museum, somehow end up at Chuen Ji Hall, catch the bus back to Taipei, visit bookshops, then return home to Shilin.Watch the video to see the tasty day unfold!

vPr-cHPMol4.title: Homemade Poke Bowl MUKBANG ft. Sashimi & Kimchi Natto
vPr-cHPMol4.description:
Hello, fellow nommers! This week we're eating a giant bowl of Homemade Poke made with salmon sashimi, yam noodles, salmon roe (fish eggs), macadamia nuts, sesame seeds, creamy avocado, sweet pickled ginger, seaweed salad and mixed greens (including baby kale, lettuce, and chard). We also sprinkle on some roasted dried seaweed and try two types of natto: organic and kimchi flavor. You are cordially invited to grab a meal and dine with me as I answer your questions from social media :)

Featured questions: 
5:30 How do I find a man that will treat me right? 
9:45 Do you get bad jet lag? If so, how do you deal with it? 
12:20 How do you get the courage to go to a new country and explore on your own? 
16:25 Can you please describe the hottest you've ever seen/met in real life? 
20:15 Have you ever been charged extra on an item for being a foreigner? I've been told to not speak English outside when traveling. 
21:13 You don't know me and I don't really know you, but I wish you will get married to me. 
21:40 Do you get worried when you try new food and you might get sick?
22:22 Do you think you will ever return to veganism? If not, can you explain what changed in your perspective? 
23:55 What is your sexual orientation?

mMKOW0Eoyxo.title: Eating Snail & Vietnamese Street Food in Hanoi
mMKOW0Eoyxo.description:
Today we're eating various Vietnamese street food with a new travel buddy! We begin the day with Egg Coffee at Cafe Giang, where we meet Nikhil. We join forces, visit the Temple of Literature and try two types of Banh Mi, snails with assorted side dishes, and gloriously golden Sweet Potato. At the end of the day, we fell in love with Vietnam all over again. Watch to see the food adventure unfold :)

D8eqa3okY8M.title: Nasi Campur in Bali ♦ Water Temple in Ubud

NxaEUni5_YY.title: Korean Convenience Store Food ft Dosirak MUKBANG
NxaEUni5_YY.description:
Greetings from Seoul! Today we're eating dosirak (Korean lunchbox), which contains japchae, pork bulgogi, seasoned zucchini and shrimp, napa cabbage kimchi, and egg tonkatsu. On top of our white rice, we sandwich dalkgalbi between five slices of cheddar cheese! How does it taste? Watch to find out! You are cordially invited to grab a meal and dine with me as we answer your questions from Instagram and Facebook :)

Featured questions: 
8:15 What is the scariest moment in your life when staying a hotel? Do you believe in ghosts? 
10:05 Who are your favorite artists and how do their works of art provide you with inspiration? 
14:30 How long would you recommend tourists to visit Korea for the first time? In the summer?

u1Ip6Rc6ny4.title: Korean Street Food MUKBANG ft Cheesy Tteokbokki
u1Ip6Rc6ny4.description:

pQfq-STJmbU.title: Raw Balinese Sambal Matah in Ubud
pQfq-STJmbU.description:
Today I share with you a chill day in Bali. I give a mini walking tour of Ubud, a go-to spot for wifi and various eats (especially for vegan and vegetarian food). We begin the day with Sambal Matah Gado-Gado with purple potato gnocchi. Then go shopping for natural mosquito repellent and an skin-smoothing clay mask. For dinner we check out a raw vegan restaurant where we try the SOL Bowl with coconut jerky and marinated zucchini. Watch to see the day unfold :)

NKsCQY28Vqg.description:
Today we try various street food in Taipei's Shilin Night Market with my housemates Kim and Steve. No joke, we tried them all! Some dishes stole my heart. Others tasted weird, but good. Haha. Watch to see the foodie adventure unfold :)

0UwKnl9s5Wg.title: North Korean Cold Noodles MUKBANG
0UwKnl9s5Wg.description:
Greetings from the other side of the world! Today we're slurping up various North Korean noodles: mul nengmyun (물 냉면), bibim nengmyun (비빔 냉면) and chogye nengmyun (초계 냉면). Mul nengmyun are cold noodles dunked in broth and topped off with slices of radish, Asian pear, cucumber and beef. Bibim nengmyun are spicy thanks to the gochujang. Chogye nengmyun is topped off with chicken. You are cordially invited to prepare a meal and eat with me :)

The camera I filmed this video with: http://amzn.to/2isP1PK

i-OaRO4Zq2w.title: Balinese Rice Terraces & Water Temple ♦ ISLAND ROAD TRIP
i-OaRO4Zq2w.description:

MsHmGOaf4y0.title: HELLO KITTY Dim Sum in Hong Kong
MsHmGOaf4y0.description:
❤️ instagram: @missminaoh
😘 subscribe for more munchies: http://bit.ly/MissMinaYT
💙 my shop: http://bit.ly/MissMinaMerch

Today we're eating cute food: Hello Kitty Dim Sum! Located in Hong Kong, everything in this restaurant has Hello Kitty's face on it. Stay long enough and she'll mark her territory on you, too. We begin the meal with Hello Kitty sausage rolls that look like spiral light bulbs. Then we segue into the Hello Kitty Birthday Bun, which has three mini buns hidden underneath. That's not all! We take a stroll around the Tsim Sha Tsui neighborhood and eat two more round of dim sum. Watch to see the food adventure unfold :)

urBa4ZGfB5c.title: Jjajangmyeon MUKBANG • Korean Black Bean Noodles
urBa4ZGfB5c.description:
Today we eat Korean Chinese food! I cook up my own version of Jjajangymeon (Korean black bean noodles). It's said to have originated from the Shandong region. When Chinese immigrants lived in Incheon, they opened up restaurants and tailored their zhajiangmian dish to suit the Korean taste bud. Thus the birth of jjajangmyeon. Btw it's also Romanized as jjajangmyun. For details on how I made my dish, read my blog post at www.minaoh.com (link below). You are cordially invited to grab your meal and eat with me! 

My recipe: https://www.missmina.co/blog/2017/5/1/jjajangmyeon-korean-black-bean-noodles-recipe

8ENJlz_s55I.title: SINGAPOREAN MUKBANG ft. Char Kway Teow, Satay & Murtabak
8ENJlz_s55I.description:
This week we're going to Singapore via our taste buds! Singapore is an island city filled with cultural influence from Malaysia, China, India and more. We try Char Kway Teow (stir-fried noodles made of bean sprout and soy sauce), Chicken Satay (seasoned and skewered meat) with peanut sauce, and Murtabak (stuffed pancake). DceuZyI6rHk.title: Vietnamese Street Food ft. Bun Dau Met
DceuZyI6rHk.description:
Today we eat Vietnamese street food, specifically Bun Dau Met (Vietnamese rice noodles with fried tofu). We also order a side of Nem (rolled sausage in rice paper). All for less than 1 USD! But first, we visit the Vietnam Military History Museum. It’s morbid to revisit memories of World War II and other atrocities. However it is essential to remember the past to prevent such acts from repeating in the future. We also stop by Ba Dinh Square and attempt to get into the Ho Chi Minh Mausoleum. Watch the travel vlog to see the day unfold!

OLJIAGHFuEI.title: German Austrian Food MUKBANG ft. Jagerschnitzel and Spatzle
OLJIAGHFuEI.description:
Today we take our taste buds to Europe! We try German Austrian cuisine: Jägerschnitzel and Spätzle. Jägerschnitzel are pork cutlets topped off with mushroom cream sauce. Back in the day, it was made with wild boar backstrap. Spätzle, also spelled as "spaetzle," are described as egg noodles and flour dumplings. You are cordially invited to prepare a meal and eat with me :)

PS: I got the food from Naschmarkt (384 E Campbell Ave, Campbell, CA 95008).

PUV0x3gKOcg.title: Afghan Food MUKBANG ● Kabuli Pulao and Kanafeh
PUV0x3gKOcg.description:
Today we dive into Afghan cuisine! We eat Kabuli Pulao, a savory Central Asian rice pilaf with lamb. For dessert we try Kanafeh, a sweet cheese pastry that will confuse your taste buds in a delicious way. For hydration we have a measuring cupful of ginseng and fresh ginger tea. You're invited to prepare a meal and eat with me! Ready or not, let's munch :)

OR_zyD2nlY8.title: Overnight Cruise in Ha Long Bay, Vietnam
OR_zyD2nlY8.description:
Today we sleepover at one of Vietnam's hottest destinations: Ha Long Bay. We take the overnight cruise and sail through its limestone islands. During the day our activities include kayaking, visiting the Thien Cung Cave, rowing by floating houses, and Vietnamese cooking lessons. In the evening we wine and dine, then go squid-fishing. No catch, but it's a way to mingle with other passengers! Watch the video to see the action unfold :)

TXg-4QNGr_U.description:

EZmwjtvK-Ss.title: Vietnamese Street Food at Hanoi Night Market
EZmwjtvK-Ss.description:
We visit the Weekend Night Market in Hanoi, Vietnam. After brief window shopping, we eat four rounds of Vietnamese food! We begin with Banh Troi Tau, a dessert made of rice balls with peanut and ginger soup. Who said you can't have dessert first? Round Two is Pho Ga (Vietnamese Chicken Noodle Soup) topped off with garlic and scallions. Then we try Banh Mi (Vietnamese Sandwich) stuffed with skewered meat. Different vendors have their own recipe. The one we have is a simple variation. We finish the day with a second round of dessert: Kem Xoi (Sticky Rice Ice Cream). PS: You’ll see Obama’s Restaurant in this video.

cRrM5OMApRk.title: Taiwanese Rice Pudding with Pork ● Tongzhi Mi Gao - 筒仔米糕
cRrM5OMApRk.description:
Ready or not, we're embarking on a food adventure through the streets of Taoyuan, Tawian! We eat Savoury Soy Milk with Egg (dou jiang - 豆漿), Soup Dumplings (xiao long bao - 小笼包), Egg Tart (danta - 蛋挞), and Savory Rice Pudding with Pork (tongzhi mi gao - 筒仔米糕). My college friend Chi Chi gives us a tour of Shung Fa, her family's herbal medicine shop. Watch the travel vlog to see the action unfold! :)

90Uu-nUU9tY.title: Stinky Tofu & Street Food at Taiwanese Night Market
90Uu-nUU9tY.description:
Today we continue our food adventure from Ximending Shopping District to Tonghua Night Market. We stop by Taipei 101 for the city view where we get to try Pineapple Cake on the 89th floor. We also eat Stinky Tofu with pickled veggies and Radish Wheel Pies. Our special guest is my college buddy Brian. He got married in Taiwan, which is what brought me to this country filled with quirky restaurants and friendly locals. Ps: You'll see knife massages and a weasel encounter in this travel vlog. Watch the video to see the action unfold :)

Brian Yu's channel: https://youtu.be/Wzz2tBD9BS4

AI10b6-PmoU.title: Gado Gado at Balinese Market & Monkey Forest
AI10b6-PmoU.description:
Today we try various food including Gado-Gado (Indonesian Vegetable Salad with Peanut Dressing), raw peanuts fresh from the field, cacao nibs and more! We also check out Bali's biggest Monkey Forest, a traditional market, a chocolate factory and the water temple of Taman Mumbul Sangeh. Travel is not all fun and games though. I wasn't aware I'd be taken to certain places and take the opportunity to raise awareness. Learning is part of travel. And we also learn how to drive through a muddy, tree-covered path on the motorbike :)

WPgr-yAChT4.title: Street Food at Gianyar Night Market in Bali, Indonesia
WPgr-yAChT4.description:

rIst3H4Esvs.title: My 6-Month Asia Trip Lookbook ► Summer, Fall & Winter Outfits
rIst3H4Esvs.description:
Six months ago I embarked on a journey across Asia, focusing mostly on Southeast Asia where the weather tends to be warm and humid. Packing light was the goal. My trip began at the end of summer and ended in winter. The following countries I visited felt like summer to me frequently or completely: Thailand, Vietnam, Singapore, Indonesia (including Bali), South Korea, Cambodia, and back to Thailand. Taiwan was a special case. I flew in for a college buddy's wedding and boy was it chilly in January! I picked up a jacket from Uniqlo, which I forgot to include in this lookbook. Just a note, I had to retire pants and shirts during my trip. A couple white pieces got stained from food and mishaps at the cleaners. Some clothes featured in this video replaced those retirees. Hope you enjoy these moving pixels as much as I had fun filming! :)

LOOK 1
+ Red plaid shirt: Uniqlo
+ Blue jeans: Zara
+ White tank with spaghetti strap: Forever 21
+ Brown bracelet with gold beading: jewellery shop in Bangkok’s Chinatown
+ Blue threaded friendship bracelet: street vendor in Chiang Mai, Thailand

SOCKS AT 0:33
+ Yellow socks with characters: La Studio Art Dealer and Vegan Cafe (Hanoi, Vietnam)
+ Red & aqua cat socks: street vendor at Myeongdong, South Korea
+ Friendship socks with green & yellow stripes: South Korea from three years ago 

LOOK 2
+ Dark grey tank: Topshop
+ Linen aqua top: Uniqlo
+ Purple eggplant pants: Forever 21

LOOK 3
+ Light blue top: H&M
+ Maroon tank with spaghetti strap: Forever 21
+ Blue jeans: Zara (same as Look 1)
+ Red & aqua cat socks: street vendor at Myeongdong
+ Roasted almonds: MaxValu Supermarket

LOOK 4: “MESSY EATING OKAY” OUTFIT
+ Dark orange plaid shirt: a very unknown brand
+ Maroon tank with spaghetti strap: Forever 21 (same as Look 3)
+ Blue jeans: Zara (same as Look 1 & 3)
+ Macadamia nuts: 7/11

LOOK 5
+ Black tank with patterned circle: Kyo (gift at a club in Singapore)
+ Purple eggplant pants: Forever 21 (same as Look 2)

LOOK 6: FEELING FESTIVE
+ Green Aladdin pants: Warorot Market in Chiang Mai, Thailand
+ Pashmina scarf: an obscure shop in Chiang Mai
+ White tank with spaghetti strap: Forever 21 (same as Look 1)

LOOK 7
+ Blue tank with California bear: some random shop in my hometown
+ Another red plaid shirt: Ruehl (defunct since 2010)
+ Purple eggplant pants: Forever 21 (same as Look 2 & 5)

LOOK 8: EVENING ATTIRE
+ Black heels: Nine West (bought in Kuta, Bali) 
+ Skirt: The Shew (bought in Seoul, South Korea)
+ Blue and gold shorts: an obscure shop in Chiang Mai
+ White top: By Kerri (bought in Seoul, South Korea)
+ White earrings: my friend in Bali gave them to me

LOOK 9: GYM UNIFORM
+ Sneakers: Nike
+ Black lounge pants: Uniqlo
+ Shirt: a library from my hometown

LOOK 10
+ White silk robe with peacock: a shop in Hoi An’s Ancient Town
+ Underwear: Victoria’s Secret

LOOK 11: PAJAMA PARTY
+ Teal shirt: a stall at Angkor Night Market in Siem Reap, Cambodia
+ Navy blue striped lounge pants: Uniqlo
+ Checkered navy shirt: Uniqlo
+ Two magenta shorts with tassels & pompoms: street vendor at Chatuchak Market in Bangkok
+ Book: “The Art of Thinking Clearly” by Rolf Dobelli
+ Zombie show on laptop: Z Nation

▼▼▼▼▼

pbhm7VjEozc.title: Christmas in Vietnam ft. Bun Thit Nuong
pbhm7VjEozc.description:
How is Christmas celebrated in Vietnam? I was in Saigon (Ho Chi Minh) at the end of December and walked around the city to get a taste of the festivities. We begin the day with an unforgettable bowl of Bún Thịt Nướng (Vietnamese Grilled Pork with Vermicelli) from a street food vendor set up two blocks away from Ben Thanh Market. Afterwards we head to Nguyen Hue Walking Street where thousands of locals gather to hang out. To see the view from above, we sit on balconies of an old apartment building converted into a community of cafes, restaurants and boutiques. We people watch, drink a whole bottle of sake, befriend locals and end the night with more tasty Vietnamese street food: Vietnamese Pizza Recipe (Bánh Tráng Nướng)! Watch to see the action unfold :)

The camera I filmed this video with: http://amzn.to/2isP1PK
The newer model of my camera: http://amzn.to/2j7X5ES

n1kA6ut7dmE.title: MY HOTEL FLOODED in Vietnam
n1kA6ut7dmE.description:
😘 Subscribe for more munchies: http://bit.ly/MissMinaYT
👕 Get my shirt: http://bit.ly/MissMinaMerch
🎥 MY CAMERA & VLOGGING GEAR: https://www.missmina.co/blog/my-2020-vlogging-gear

Due to heavy rain for days, Hoi An flooded during my trip. It was my first time to experience walking in muddy waters. Some parts of the road were deep, so we ended up riding a boat through the streets. Walking in water is a resistance workout and you're not able to see where you step. Your feet get caught in sunken debris every other block. Regardless, I vlogged it! The flood eventually rose and covered the lobby, dining area and pool. The guests and I were escorted to Danang, one hour north of Hoi An. Watch the action unfold :) Note: Thanks to Nhi Nhi Hotel for getting us to higher grounds!

I0yLzSCuv9I.title: Indonesian Street Food in Jakarta (ft. Rando, Felicia, Nadia Vega)
I0yLzSCuv9I.description:
Today we eat various Indonesian street food in Jakarta with special guests Nadia Vega, Fransiska Felicia & Laurentius Rando. The featured dishes include: Bakso (meatball soup), Somay (steamed fish dumpling), Satay Padang (skewered meat), Sop Kaki Kambing (goat leg soup with testicles and brain), Sate Kambing (grilled goat meat), Kelapa Jeruk (iced citrus coconut drink), Pisang Bakar (cheesy banana with chocolate), Roti Bakar (toasted bread with cheese and chocolate), and last but most definitely not least, the delicious Kerak Kelor (traditional spicy omelette). Watch to find out what they taste like! Note: you can try these delicious dishes across the Kalibata Heroes Cemetery (Taman Makam Pahlawan Kalibata).

Laurentius Rando Channel: https://www.youtube.com/LRando

rPeM2VmeDWo.title: THAI STREET FOOD at Warorot Market ● Khao Tom Mad, Khao Kan Chin, Khanom Krok & Assorted Desserts
rPeM2VmeDWo.description:
Today we head over to Chiang Mai's Warorot Market for scrumptious Thai street food. We dine on Khao Kan Chin (rice with blood), Khao Tom Mad (sticky rice parcels with banana), our beloved Khanom Krok (coconut pudding pancakes), and assorted Thai desserts. As we search for traditional handmade goods of Northern Thailand style, we come across Ton Lamyai Flower Market. On the walk back to our hostel, we stop by temples Wat Lamchang and Wat Chiang Man. Watch to see the action unfold! :)

mPBd7wft4FU.title: Khao Soi Noodles & Thai Coconut Cookies ● First Day in Chiang Mai, Thailand
mPBd7wft4FU.description:
What does one do on the first day in Chiang Mai? Eat Northern Thai food, of course! There's no time to lose. We head out to try Khao Soi upon a short nap to recover from the overnight train from Bangkok. Khao Soi is coconut curry soup with noodles. It is a Burmese-influenced dish also popularly consumed in Laos. We then explore the neighborhood filled with temples. In the search for fresh baby coconuts, we encounter Thai street food. Watch to see the adventure unfold :)

yOKeIV5WFnI.title: Thai Street Food at Chatuchak Weekend Market
yOKeIV5WFnI.description:
Today my local Thai friend gives us a food & shopping tour of Chatuchak Weekend Market (also known as: JJ Market). And yes, they are only open during the weekend! After multiple rounds of indulging in Thai street food, we head over to Asiatique and try freshly-pressed Octopus Crackers. The hissing sounds like a hundred octopuses proclaiming revenge. We finish the evening with more Thai food. 

Featured foods: 
Chicken Noodle Soup at Wait For
Coconut Ice Cream
Kanom Gui Chai (Fried Chive Cakes)
Khao Pad ข้าวผัด (Fried Rice)
Kiew Tod Kai Nook Gata (Fried Quail Egg)
Miang Kham เมี่ยงคำ (One-Bite Wraps)
Nam Tok Moo น้ำตกหมู  (Meat Salad)
Som Tum  ส้มตำ (Green Papaya Salad)
Thapthim Krop ทับทิมกรอบ (Thai Red Rubies Dessert)

After multiple rounds of indulging in Thai street food, we head over to Asiatique and try freshly-pressed Octopus Crackers. The hissing sounds like a hundred octopuses proclaiming revenge. We finish the evening with more Thai food. 

Featured foods: 
Chicken Noodle Soup at Wait For
Coconut Ice Cream
Kanom Gui Chai (Fried Chive Cakes)
Khao Pad ข้าวผัด (Fried Rice)
Kiew Tod Kai Nook Gata (Fried Quail Egg)
Miang Kham เมี่ยงคำ (One-Bite Wraps)
Nam Tok Moo น้ำตกหมู  (Meat Salad)
Som Tum  ส้มตำ (Green Papaya Salad)
Thapthim Krop ทับทิมกรอบ (Thai Red Rubies Dessert)

nmeRPpSfx5Q.title: Nightlife at Bangkok's Chinatown ● Yaowarat Street Food during Vegetarian Festival
nmeRPpSfx5Q.description:
It's Friday night in Bangkok and we're heading over to Chinatown. By coincidence we visit on the first day of Thailand's Vegetarian Festival. Triangular yellow flags sway through the streets, indicating Jay food (which is similar to veganism but avoids the use of pungent ingredients such as garlic, onions, scallions, etc). We try various dishes ranging from savory to sweet and vegan to omnivore.

F4EvYXBwF6A.description:
Greetings from the Land of Smiles! Today my high school friend Sera joins me on the Bangkok adventures. We dig into Thai street food culture and fall in love with Khanom Krok (Coconut Pudding Pancakes). These cute and crunchy bites are better than a boyfriend! Eat it to believe it. 

Upon brunch at a Thai hipster restaurant, we head over to Saphan Taksin for a boat ride up the Chao Phraya River. Without a set itinerary, we find ourselves exploring Wat Pho and savoring its calming beauty. Watch to see the action unfold!

Places featured: 
Bitterman
Chao Phraya River
Khanom Krok stall on Sala Daeng Alley 1
Wat Arun
Wat Pho (aka: Wat Po)

ZORR7tLt7Ac.title: Thai Steamed Dumplings - Khao Kriab Pak Moh ● Thailand Travel Vlog
ZORR7tLt7Ac.description:
Going to the hospital when visiting another country is usually not desired, but boy was I happy to have experienced it in Bangkok! Bumrungrad Hospital felt more like a hotel than anything else. 

Coincidentally my doctor's appointment landed on the same day as my dental appointment. Both places happened to be within blocks of each other near the infamous red light district of Nana. 

With six hours to kill, we get a 2-hour massage for only $16 USD and savor a freshly-cut young coconut right next to a railroad track. Because it was Monday, many street food stalls closed due to street cleaning. However we do come across vendors who sell Khao Kriab Pak Moh (Thai steamed dumplings) and Sakhu Sai Moo (Tapioca Balls with pork filling). 

As an early dinner, we try vegetarian Indian food at Khana Khazana. Then befriend the kind receptionist at the dental clinic for dinner at Bangkok's Koreantown. What a day filled with diverse happenings!

hdLhKzd7IA0.title: THAI STREET FOOD MUKBANG ● filmed in Bangkok at my loft
hdLhKzd7IA0.description:
Greetings from Thailand! My knee is still recovering, so haven't been able to venture out much. Fortunately there's a ton of street food in my neighborhood, thus mukbang ensues :) You're invited to grab a meal and eat with me! Now let's bite into some exotic flavors~

ps: Thank you to everyone kindly telling me the names and details of each food :) 

ps #2: Anjle R wrote a very detailed description of the various Thai foods I tried in this mukbang. Kup kuhn ka! I've copied and pasted her comment here so you can read as well. She wrote: 
In the order of what you tried: 
1. Khao Krieb Pak Mor (a snack prepared by pouring rice flour-based batter over a muslin cloth covering a steamer, filling it with a mixture of ground peanuts, coriander, palm sugar, other seasonings, and sometimes pork - this type of dumpling is just folded over the filling as the skin gets cooked, and not shaped before cooking) 
2. Phad Hoy Lai (simply means stir-fried clams - the liquid is from seasoning sauces and natural juices from the clam... chili paste is part of the seasoning and so it gives that color ...definitely not a curry) 
3. Khai Cha-Om (omelet with acacia pennata ...popular side dish, and Thai omelets are always cooked in woks with more oil than regular western omelets so you get that "fluffy" interior with a crisp exterior) 
4. Khao Tom Mud (can be eaten as a dessert of a breakfast, consists of glutinous rice, coconut milk, sugar, black beans, and the filling is banana ... wrapped in banana leaves and steamed) 
5. Plaa Tod Sam Rod (Fried fish with 3 flavors sauce - ideally spicy, sweet, sour, with the sweetness being the leading taste) 
6. Phad Phed Nor Mai (stir-fried bamboo shoots dish, cooked with garlic, chili, oyster sauce, fish sauce, and the fragrance you're smelling is a mixture of sweet basil and keffir lime leaves) 
7. Gai Tod (Thai fried chicken - Thai marinades for grilled and fried meats generally consist of garlic, coriander root, pepper, soy sauce, and sugar... the dipping sauce is essentially sugar syrup, salt, garlic, chili) 
8. Guen Gai Yang (grilled chicken gizzards .... yup!) 
9. Moo Ping (grilled pork meat)

GdQG3HjfLPE.title: Korean Airplane Food ♦ Bibimbap on Asiana Flight OZ741 from Seoul to Bangkok
GdQG3HjfLPE.description:
How does Korean food taste in airplanes? I ride on Asiana Airlines from Seoul to Bangkok and try their Bibimbap paired with Fish Soup. Their in-flight meal came with a side of napa cabbage kimchi and fruit (watermelon, apple). A mini mukbang ensues :)

As we departed Incheon International Airport, I noticed there were many empty seats in the back. The seat next to mine was empty as well! It was awesome. Everyone made makeshift beds out of them :) About one hour into the ride, we were served dinner. 

After watching "Angry Birds" and taking a nap in the posture of a baby in a womb, we arrived at Suvarnabhumi Airport past midnight.

It’s my last full day in Korea and I ordered a bunch of food I haven’t eaten yet during this trip: Kimchi jjigae, nengmyun, bibimguksu, and deopbap! Grab your meal and let’s eat together as we talk about the textures of these Korean dishes and the flavours of life :)

The camera I filmed this video with: http://amzn.to/2isP1PK
The newer model of my camera: http://amzn.to/2j7X5ES

c5s-p74btQI.title: MUKBANG IN BED with Korean Food ■ Kimchi, Bean Sprout Soup, Duck Salad
c5s-p74btQI.description:
Welcome to my first mukbang video from Korea! It's been a hot and humid summer so far, but thankfully not as sizzling as I initially imagined. I've been filming lots of travel vlogs and eating flavorful dishes, so for today's mukbang, we eat healthy and light Korean food to balance things out. You are cordially invited to prepare a meal and eat with me :) PS: Sorry for the belated upload today! My laptop was overheating during the export process and I had to give it a break. Even technology needs rest!

NOTABLE MOMENTS: 
00:43 Eat this to reverse baldness and get dark hair again!
1:15 Bean Sprout Soup
1:52 Kimchi and multi-grained rice
3:08 Summer weather in Korea. How hot and humid is it?
4:30 My routine while traveling 
4:40 How I workout when abroad 
6:57 Where to watch my Korea travel vlogs
7:10 Revenge of the stubborn duck
8:21 Books are like people
9:33 I wonder if I belong here
10:30 Luck is a subjective adjective 
11:01 Partying in Los Angeles vs Singapore 
12:35 How rich do you need to be to travel? 
13:40 There are more languages than the spoken kind
14:26 I love it when this happens 
14:55 Travel as an escape. How effective is it? 

WHERE I GOT THE GOODS: 
Moomyung Shikdang
50 Seongbuk-ro, Seongbuk-gu, Seoul
Phone: 02-743-1733
Note: Their menu changes all the time so you’ll never get bored!

KUaT2eubXBo.title: THAI FOOD MUKBANG with corn cakes & green curry
KUaT2eubXBo.description:
Sawatdeekah with a wai :) That’s a Thai greeting as you slightly bow with palms together. Why? Because today we’re eating Thai cuisine! Growing up I always ordered Penang Curry at Thai restaurants, but today I get adventurous and try Corn Cakes for the first time. For the entree? Green Curry! You are cordially invited to prepare a meal and eat with me :)

m9Ss6OMwUMs.title: CAMBODIAN FOOD MUKBANG with fish amok & papaya salad
m9Ss6OMwUMs.description:
Chomreabsuor! That means “hello” in Cambodian. Or so Google Translate says (which one should not trust 100%). In today’s mukbang, we bite into the scrumdiddlyumptious Fish Amok. We pair it with a spicy Green Papaya Salad, which pregnant ladies should be wary of. Let’s get this party in the mouth started! You are cordially invited to bring your meal to the table and eat with me :)

9wNBRhSqg2Y.title: JAMAICAN FOOD MUKBANG with jerk pork, festival, key lime pie and more
9wNBRhSqg2Y.description:
In today's mukbang, we enjoy Caribbean cuisine. We start off with a Festival, the Jamaican Cornbread Fritter that is cushiony and tastes like a party starter! Then we dig into the Jerk Pork. X19IA4mMykQ.title: BURMESE FOOD MUKBANG with tea leaf salad & sanwinmakin
X19IA4mMykQ.description:
Mingalaba! That means “Hello” in Burmese :) For today’s mukbang, we try the famous Tea Leaf Salad thanks to our fellow viewers’ requests. I love how the tangy fermented leaves are used to flavor the salad, as opposed to how in the U.S. we drizzle our greens with a liquidy dressing. For dessert we give Sanwanmakin a shot, topped off with vanilla ice cream. This mukbang is shorter than the ones I’ve uploaded previously. Let me know if you prefer the longer mukbang or this condensed version :)

bVIu5TJunJw.title: FILIPINO FOOD MUKBANG with chicken adobo, turon, ube ice cream
bVIu5TJunJw.description:
Kamusta? That's "hello" in Tagalog :) Yup, yup. Today we're enjoying Filipino food! A fellow viewer recommended Chicken Adobo and Turon, so that's I try. Dessert comes with the unicorn-liciously purple Ube Ice Cream. Boy oh boy, is it delicious! If I were a kid without self-control, I'd be eating this all day long. You're bound to get hungry watching this, so I cordially invite you to grab your meal and let's eat together. PS: Thanks for much for your suggestions on where to visit in the Philippines! jqB-bfYb3vU.description:
Vegan Mexican food? Yup, it exists! We head to Adelita's where they serve both omnivore and vegan Mexican cuisine. Don't forget to try their Churro with Ice Cream. Its sugar-coasted crunchy exterior conceals a gooey caramel filling. Smiles guaranteed! Pair those warm sweet sticks with cool ice cream and life is complete. Watch the food adventure for more details :)

Adelita's is where people of all types of diets can share one dinner table. For strictly vegan food, try Gracias Madre in SF and LA.

plcb29t2NGo.title: Dilli Haat Food Festival in California
plcb29t2NGo.description:
Inspired by India's open-air food plaza in Delhi, the Dilli Haat Food Festival is a congregation of mouthwatering flavors and enchanting performances. With traditional and modern dances lined up back-to-back all afternoon, your eyes will be continuously stimulated from the vibrant colors. Be sure to come early as lines to get food become increasingly long by the hour. When you bite into your uttapam of golden crisp, you'll agree that it was worth the 30-minute wait. The only regret? Not buying more! Worth every cent and calorie. Watch to see the event unfold! 

Note: Event hosted by WomenNow TV at DeAnza College.

9wnApDWmdAg.title: Hong Kong Style Dim Sum MUKBANG Q&A
9wnApDWmdAg.description:
Are you ready for my longest mukbang ever? You might get hungry, so feel free to prepare a meal and let’s eat together :) Let me know what you’re munching on in the comment section! 

NOTABLE MOMENTS: 
1:10 Unboxing begins. Introducing the cast. 
1:25 Enter the Wife Cake. Oops, I mean Sponge Cake. 
7:15 First bite. The flamboyant dumpling begins the party. 
8:50 First question: Are you following your dreams? 
9:35 I interrupt myself. It's one of my hobbies.
10:25 Getting to your dream is like going through the process of going through many boyfriends and finally meeting Prince Charming. Kinda. 
13:15 First bite into Steamed Sponge Cake that looks like construction material.
14:15 Following your dreams (part 3)
15:45 Snapchat break.
15:55 Going faster is not always better.
16:13 First bite into Chive Dumpling.
17:00 You can’t pursue ten dreams.
18:30 Meet the talking Chui Chow Dumpling.
20:10 I’m pretty sure this is Shumai.
20:35 Don’t even ask.
21:00 Beef Shumai. Tastes like rice, but with a different texture.
21:25 No dream? Pursue your interests. 
21:45 How long does it take to edit a video? 
22:25 Hello, Shrimp Dumping.
23:07 We eventually will get to the Chicken Feet. One of these days. One of these minutes…
23:50 First bite into the squished mystery bun with purple paste. Must be taro.
25:10 I eat like a man. I show you my pajamas. 
25:57 These feel like a butt… but even better. 
27:00 Peanut VS Red Bean
27:24 Can I marry this Coconut Ball? It may be the best thing that ever happened to me. 
28:15 Thick yet soft skin
28:55 Reminds me of mochi and chapssaltteok. I could eat a hundred of these.
29:30 Expectation VS Reality
30:05 How did you overcome that dark period in college when you felt lonely? 
31:00 Your environment and surrounding people influence your identity.
32:30 Burping like a lady
33:03 First bite into sweet and meaty bun. Aka: BBQ Pork Pastry. It’s like eating a meal and dessert at the same time.
33:40 How to overcome being lonely in college (part 2) 
34:20 Misery loves company
35:20 What everyone agrees about LA
36:00 Develop a routine to feel at home
36:30 Holy moly! Did you hear that crispy sound? The Sesame Ball wins the best soundtrack for this mukbang! So far. 
37:24 This ball is not symmetrical. Always a surprise to bite into. 
38:28 Loneliness (part 3) 
39:00 Shrimp and Pepper. Crunchity crunch crunch. 
39:29 The bathroom door closes by itself
39:50 Baked Custard Bun. Looks like a dino egg. Mmmmm.
41:45 Adults and kids will like this
42:03 It’s not fair.
43:15 Forgive me, Wife Cake. For you are really Steamed Sponge Cake.
43:30 What is the most unusual experience you’ve had in a foreign country? Or any uncomfortable situation? 
43:50 But first, the Egg Tart!
44:40 First bite into the Egg Tart. Soft and silky. Hearts in my eyes.
46:40 This dropped from heaven
47:10 First bite into the Chicken Feet. Jelly, boney, bumpy. 
47:46 Battery life dying alert
48:40 WOAH!!! THE CRISP! 
49:22 I can’t get over this crisp. My life is complete. 
49.40 Answering “What is the most unusual experience you’ve had in a foreign country? Or any uncomfortable situation?” 
50:21 CENSORED. I was debating on keeping this part in or not. I decided to take it out since I have some young viewers as well. 
50:25 Everywhere you go, you learn something about yourself and other people. 
52:10 Battery dies. So we switch over to the second camera. 
52:52 Another bite of Egg Tart. Cannot resist. 

WHERE I GOT THE MUNCHIES:
Tai Pan Dim Sum Bakery
477 Saratoga Ave
San Jose, CA 95129
Tel: (408) 247-9996

https://www.youtube.com/user/sweetandtasty

Ad1-85W7pD8.title: Portugal Day 2016 in California
Ad1-85W7pD8.description:
June 10th is Day of Portugal, called Dia de Portugal in the native language. We join the festivities at Kelley Park in San Jose for vibrant folk dances, live music, traditional parade, art and book expositions, and Portuguese food. Hope you come with an empty stomach because there's a lot of tasty options. From Portuguese Fava Beans to Piri Piri Fries, you'll be wanting to try them all. There's a reason why the lines for food are long! 

Today's Performers: 
Comedian Taylor Amarante
Musician Chico Avila
Dance & music by Mar Alto from Hilmar

je4YvPIWFns.title: ETHIOPIAN FOOD Family Style with Meat & Vegetarian Combo
je4YvPIWFns.description:
Today we travel to Africa through our taste buds! Appropriately it's a hot day and we head over to Zeni Ethiopian Restaurant. My childhood friend joins us for the food adventure as we share a huge family-style plate of injera and wot. She likes meat and I like veggies, so we order the Vegetarian and Meat Combo. Be sure to wash your hands because they're the traditional utensils used for eating Ethiopian food. We then attempt our very first gursha! It's a bonding moment where you feed others at the table :)

Zeni Ethiopian Restaurant
1320 Saratoga Ave
San Jose, CA 95129

Vegetarian combo comes with ye-miser wot (lentil), ye-kik alitcha (split peas), atalkelt wot (vegetables), ye-gomen wot and ye timatim fitfit.

Meat combo comes with ye-beg alitcha wot (lamb), doro wot (chicken), kitfo (beef) and homemade cottage cheese.

kxatLJnqpZs.title: World's Crookedest Street | Lombard in SF
kxatLJnqpZs.description:
Today we hike uphill to what is said to be the world's most crooked street. And in the very least, the most crooked street in San Francisco! Though spanning only one block on Lombard Street, this windy road of eight turns attracts plenty of tourists and their selfies. For a more scenic view of the city, off we head to Coit Tower. A must-visit place on a clear day, especially for observing the Golden Gate Bridge, Alcatraz Island, Transamerica Pyramid and more!

QBGsWMC4D1Q.title: Korean Food in San Francisco
QBGsWMC4D1Q.description:
Where's the best Korean food in San Francisco? My relative and friends say it's Han Il Kwan, so I venture to the west and try their food for myself. The number of complimentary side dishes are no joke! In addition, there was no major food coma afterwards. A sign that little or no MSG is used! Two thumbs up. The flavors range more on the mild side. It is said many older Koreans flock to dine here, which is no surprise as the food is not Westernized. Westernized Korean food tends to be overly sweet, salty, spicy, etc. After a colorful feast, we head on over to Legion of Honor and a leisure drive through Presidio. Watch to find out for a detailed look at the Korean food and fun!

P0NmF2D8KyQ.title: Traveling to San Francisco
P0NmF2D8KyQ.description:
Join me on the journey to San Francisco! The minute upon arrival, I head over to a restaurant called Unicorn. Yup, you heard that right. Unicorn, haha. It’s a place I’ve been meaning to try after driving by it so many times. They serve Pan-Asian cuisine catering to diverse types of diets. I order the vegan Bean Curd with Spicy Mango & Chinese Eggplant, accompanied with Coconut Wild Black Rice. Afterwards I attend the Wanderlust Blog Party Workshop held at PicsArt Studio, where my previous boss and other cool peeps introduce themselves. Watch to see the action unfold!

HqmZP0ISkfU.title: 21 Things To Do in Singapore
HqmZP0ISkfU.description:
Thank you to all my friends who made Singapore feel like home for nearly two years. I dedicate this video to you. Especially because you showed me how to party at these places :)

My best friend Nadia Vega (who appears in this vlog) just made a new YouTube channel! She's a talented actress and musician from Indonesia. Subscribe to her here: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCEVQV170FgCchObxnW3eSpQ

PLACES FEATURED INCLUDE: 
Ananda Bhavan (for vegetarian Indian food)
Bollywood Veggies
Buddha Tooth Relic Temple
Bugis Street
Chinese Theatre Circle
Chomp Chomp Food Centre
Club Street
F Club at Clarke Quay
Gardens By The Bay
Geylang
Hay Dairies
Holland Village
Jurong Frog Farm
Koreatown in Tanjong Pagar
Kranji Countryside
Leong Kee (Klang) Bak Kut Teh
Mama Kong's (for chili crab and buns)
Marina Bay Sands
Masjid Sultan at Arab Street
Maxwell Food Centre
Mei Heong Yuan Dessert (for ice kachang)
Merlion Statue
Mu Parlour (for charcoal bun burgers)
Mustafa Centre at Little India
Orchard Road
Pagoda Street in Chinatown
Selfie Coffee at Haji Lane
Singapore Botanic Gardens
Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple
Star Vista
Tanjong Beach Club at Sentosa
The Screening Room

jTd1IzTYlBM.title: WHY I'M IN LA
jTd1IzTYlBM.description:
Today I reveal to you why I came to Los Angeles. Hint hint: hosting gig! The morning starts off with a shopping trip for vegan snacks. Shortly after I head on over to a cafe in Koreatown LA to meet the producers of Bachelor to discuss our script. Not hungry, but always having room saved for vegan food, my bestie and I visit Cafe Gratitude yet again! Take a peek at LA's Art District as we walk through galleries and exhibitions :)
